<Callout type="warning" title="Wrong mode = wrong reading">
  Measuring AC voltage on a DC multimeter setting will give a near-zero reading — the meter will show only the DC offset (if any) and ignore the alternating component. Always verify your mode selector before taking a measurement.
</Callout>

<h2 id="why-ac-won">Why AC Won the Distribution War</h2>

<p>In the 1880s, Thomas Edison championed DC distribution while Nikola Tesla and George Westinghouse advocated for AC. AC won for one decisive reason: <strong>transformers</strong>. A transformer can step AC voltage up to hundreds of kilovolts for long-distance transmission (reducing current and therefore resistive losses by the square), then step it back down for safe use at homes and factories. No equivalent device exists for DC.</p>

<p>India's national grid transmits at 400 kV, 220 kV, and 132 kV AC. By the time it reaches your workshop or factory, it has been stepped down through multiple substations to 11 kV, then 415/230 V. This entire chain is only possible because the supply is AC. Modern HVDC (High Voltage DC) transmission is now used for some ultra-long corridors — but it still requires AC at both ends and expensive converter stations in between.</p>

<h2 id="safety">Safety Considerations</h2>

<p>Both AC and DC carry lethal risk at mains voltages, but they behave differently on the human body:</p>

<div class="my-6 space-y-3">
  {[
    { label: 'AC at 50 Hz', detail: 'Particularly dangerous because 50 Hz is close to the frequency that can cause ventricular fibrillation. AC tends to cause muscular tetanus — the victim cannot let go of the conductor. The let-go threshold is approximately 6–9 mA for AC.' },
    { label: 'DC above 60 V', detail: 'DC causes a single strong muscular contraction that may throw the victim clear — but this can itself cause injury from the fall. DC burns tend to be more severe at the entry and exit points. Battery systems above 60 V DC are classified as hazardous.' },
    { label: 'High frequency AC', detail: 'At very high frequencies (above ~100 kHz), current flows on the skin surface rather than through the body core — this is the basis of RF diathermy in medicine. Standard mains AC at 50 Hz does NOT benefit from this effect.' },
  ].map(item => (
    <div class="flex gap-4 p-4 bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-xl">
      <div class="shrink-0 w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-amber-500 flex items-center justify-center">
        <span class="text-white text-base font-bold">!</span>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="font-bold text-amber-900 text-sm">{item.label}</div>
        <div class="text-xs text-amber-800 mt-0.5">{item.detail}</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  ))}
</div>

<Callout type="tip" title="Always use CAT-rated instruments">
  When measuring on mains circuits, use instruments rated CAT II (household sockets), CAT III (distribution boards, fixed installations), or CAT IV (service entrance, energy meters). Never use a CAT I instrument or an unrated meter on mains circuits — transient overvoltages can exceed the meter's withstand capability and cause arc flash or explosion.
</Callout>

